The user is saying the backtick characters are still appearing around inline code elements. My previous fix of setting `content: ''` in `global.css` might not have worked, or there's another source of the backticks.

Let me check the current state of `global.css` to see if my change was applied correctly. The backtick issue might be coming from the Tailwind Typography plugin (prose) which also adds backticks to `code` elements via `::before`/`::after`.

Looking at Tailwind Typography's default styles, it adds:
```css
.prose code::before {
  content: '`';
}
.prose code::after {
  content: '`';
}
```

So even though I fixed `article :not(pre) > code::before/::after`, the `.prose` class on the article element is still adding backticks via the Tailwind Typography plugin! I need to override the prose plugin's code pseudo-elements too by adding rules to remove the backticks from `.prose code::before` and `.prose code::after` in `global.css` or through the Tailwind config.

Overriding the prose styles... I need to ensure the `!important` flag overrides the Tailwind Typography plugin's backtick styles, or add a more specific rule targeting the `.prose` class directly to remove those pseudo-element decorations.

